<table bgcolor="white" width="100%"><tr><td style="font-family: Verdana, Arial font-size: 8pt color: black">
				<B>Document List: <A HREF="/modules.php?op=modload&amp;name=Documents&amp;file=index&id=8" style="text-decoration: none;">.:: Guild Charter ::.</A>&nbsp;
<A HREF="/modules.php?op=modload&amp;name=Documents&amp;file=index&id=31" style="text-decoration: none;">.:: Code of Conduct ::.</A>&nbsp;
<A HREF="/modules.php?op=modload&amp;name=Documents&amp;file=index&id=29" style="text-decoration: none;">.:: Raid Procedures ::.</A>&nbsp;
<br>
</B>
				<table border="0" bgcolor="gray" 
				width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr>
				<td style="color: ivory; padding: 4px" colspan="2">
				<span STYLE="font-size: 11pt; font-weight: bold;">&nbsp;&nbsp;Loot Guidelines</span>
				</td></tr>
				<tr>
					<td align="left" bgcolor="white" style="font-size: 8pt">
					<A HREF="/modules.php?op=modload&amp;name=Documents&amp;file=index&id=28" style="text-decoration: none; font-size: x-small;">[contents]</A>
					</td>
					<td align="right" bgcolor="white" style="font-size: 8pt">
					<a href="javascript:history.go(-1)" style="text-decoration: none; font-size: x-small;">[back]</a>
					&nbsp;
					&nbsp;
					&nbsp;
					&nbsp;
					</td>
				</tr>
				</table><BR><b><u>Loot Guidelines</u></b><br>
<br>
KoL has a Need before Greed policy. "Need" of an item is defined as any item that you would immediately equip and use for a good length of game time, possibly for the rest of your EQ career. Greed is defined as looting an item for the profit alone without regard to who can benefit most from any item dropped. A good example would be to force a roll on the Celestial Healing spell for clerics instead of giving the spell to the cleric already in the group. In such a situation it is obvious that the cleric should be given the spell regardless, based on the fact that he can use it and would gain far more benefit from it than anyone else in the group.<br>
<br>
When an item drops, determine first who can use it. In the event that no one has a use for it, roll on it normally. If only one person has a need they get it by default. If more than one person present has a definite need for the item, all persons involved that have a need should roll for the item. Once someone wins an item, they should refrain from taking any more until everyone has gotten something, unless another item drops that they and only they are best suited to use.<br>
<br>
Quest items always go to those who need them for epic quests, based on the level of the player in relation to the quest. For epic items, the highest-level player present should be given the item since they are closer to their goal.<br>
<br>
If you loot and equip a good item, consider donating the item it replaced to the group you are with so that everyone else has something to roll on. This way everyone gets something. At any guild events and raids, officers will handle all of the loot. They will decide who gets what items based on the status of those within the guild. Respect their decisions. Under no circumstances will the need of a twink player or secondary character be considered in our loot policies. We are only concerned with our main characters. <br>
<br>
Do not attempt to misrepresent your need of a certain item, just be honest. We will not look kindly on anyone who is attempting to abuse the need before greed policy. You don't even want to know what will happen to you if we see you selling something you got from the guild on the pretense of need before greed. Luclin guilds have a policy whereby if you are found trading away an item you got at a raid on the pretense of need, you will be blacklisted from further raids and put on to a "no res" list that will greatly reduce your chance of appealing to clerics for resurrections, among other things. It's an instant and nearly irreversible way to get a black stain on the reputation of your character. Our guild has no need of those players with tainted reputations.<br>
<br>
When rolling for loot items, we use the seed method. The group leader will do a /rand 500 1000 and the seed will be generated. Everyone will then /rand to the number the group leader rolled. This provides a better degree of randomness than the usual /rand 100 that most pickup groups use.<br>
<br>
If you are not grouped with guild members but with a general pickup group, you can expect the loot rules to be vastly different. Lower-level players by nature are mostly greedy; whereas you will find that higher-level players in higher-level zones almost universally use the need before greed rules. Any time you join a pickup group, your first question should be what the loot rules are. Force this issue out into the open up front instead of waiting until something good drops. This will help you to avoid being taken for a ride. If the loot rules don't sit well with you, leaving the group is usually a good decision.<br>
